Upon that book he must have been engaged in the summer of 45, for as early as May we find him ask- ing Atticus for books on the subject.1 Mueh of the same material reappears in the Cato, not as though copied from the earlier work, but with every appearance of a free re- casting from memory‚ thus implying a comparatively short interval between the first book of the T asculan Disputa- tions and the Cato. Yet this point is not to be urged too strongly, for the reason that many of the arguments con- cerned were of a stereotyped order, and the illustrations commonplaces.

The book was written in haste, and some months later revised with equal haste.2 Cicero himself in a letter to Atticus3 speaks of sending him the Cato revised crebris locis. Not a few of the defects in logical connection may perhaps be traced back to this double recension.
